############################################################ # PG Setup ############################################################ Context('Numeric');
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML In a recent survey, 30 students reported whether they liked their potatoes Mashed, French-fried, or Twice-baked. 15 liked them mashed, 20 liked French fries, and 9 liked twice baked potatoes. Additionally, 12 students liked both mashed and fried potatoes, 5 liked French fries and twice baked potatoes, 6 liked mashed and baked, and 3 liked all three styles. How many students _hate_ potatoes? Explain why your answer is correct.
[_____]{6}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION Using the principle of inclusion/exclusion, the number of students who like their potatoes in at least one of the ways described is
[``` 15 + 20 + 9 - 12 - 5 - 6 + 3 = 24. ```]
Therefore there are [`30-24 = 6`] students who do not like potatoes. You can also do this problem with a Venn diagram.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
