############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Suppose you are ordering a large pizza from _D.P.[$NBSP]*Dough_. You want 3 distinct toppings, chosen from their list of 11 vegetarian toppings. a. How many choices do you have for your pizza?
[_____]{$ans1}
a. How many choices do you have for your pizza if you refuse to have pineapple as one of your toppings?
[_____]{$ans2}
a. How many choices do you have for your pizza if you _insist_ on having pineapple as one of your toppings?
[_____]{$ans3}
a. How do the three questions above relate to each other? Explain.
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`{11 \choose 3} = 165`] choices, since you have to select a 3-element subset of the set of 11 toppings. a. [`{10 \choose 3} = 120`] choices, since you must select 3 of the 10 non-pineapple toppings. a. [`{10 \choose 2} = 45`] choices, since you must select 2 of the remaining 10 non-pineapple toppings to have in addition to the pineapple. a. [`165 = 120 + 45`] choices, which makes sense because every 3-topping pizza either has pineapple or does not have pineapple as a topping.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
